at||fp||cp||at|^^
Now that you are familiar (and hopefully comfortable) with attitude signals, it is time to turn our attention to the study of another type of defensive signal: count signals. Here is a reminder of the purpose of using count signals and the messages that these signals convey:

|
qx|3.2|
pg| ***** 0 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{ Count signals are used to tell your partner whether you have an even 
 (2, 4, 6, or 8) or an odd (1, 3, 5, or 7) number of cards in a specific suit. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 1 ***** |


at|So count signals are used to describe the number of cards that a player holds in a given suit, but these signals do not reveal the exact number of cards that the signaler holds. Count signals specify only whether the number of cards held is even (2, 4, 6, or 8) or odd (1, 3, 5, or 7).

It is up to the partner of the player who makes a count signal to try to figure out the exact number of cards that his partner holds in a given suit. A lot of the time he will be able to use factors like the count signal that he received, the bidding, and inferences from the way the play has gone so far to figure out exactly how many cards his partner was dealt in each suit. As we have seen:

|
pg| ***** 2 ***** |


cs|3|at|^-{ Defense becomes a lot easier when you can figure out the contents of the unseen hands! }
^-
|
pg| ***** 3 ***** |


at|Attitude signals can help a defender figure out the location of key missing honor cards and count signals can help a defender figure out the distribution of the unseen hands. By using both of these types of signals, the defenders are often in a position to tell each other everything they need to know in order to defend accurately. |
pg| ***** 4 ***** |


tb||

nt|^b@2^z@3
Here are the basic mechanics of how count signals work:

|
pg| ***** 5 ***** |


cs|1|at|^-{ Play a high card to show your partner that you have an even number of cards in that suit. 
 Play a low card to show your partner that you have an odd number of cards in that suit. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 6 ***** |


at|It would be natural for you to be somewhat confused after reading the above description of how count signals work. You have already learned that a defender can play a high card as an encouraging attitude signal or a low card as a discouraging attitude signal. Now you are being told that high and low cards can also be used as count signals. How is a defender supposed to know whether his partner is signaling attitude or count?

|
pg| ***** 7 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{ The situation in which a signal is made determines the type of signal that is being used. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 8 ***** |


at|We have already seen that attitude signals are used only in a few well-defined situations. The same is true of count signals. There are 2 main situations in which a defender should give a count signal:

|
pg| ***** 9 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{ 1. Signal count when the declarer leads a suit from his hand or from the dummy. }

|
pg| ***** 10 ***** |


cs|3|at|{ 2. Signal count if your attitude toward a suit is already known. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 11 ***** |


at|Later in this chapter we will encounter one other situation where a defender should give his partner a count signal. |
pg| ***** 12 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|n#|5|at|The same warnings that apply to attitude signals should be kept in mind when giving count signals as well. In particular:

|
pg| ***** 13 ***** |


cs|1|at|^-{ Winning tricks takes priority over giving accurate signals! Don't forget about things 
 like second hand low, third hand high, and splitting honors for the sake of signaling! }

|
pg| ***** 14 ***** |


cs|4|at|{ Always signal with the loudest card that you can afford to play. The clearer your signals are, 
 the more likely it will be that your partner will get the message that you were trying to convey! }

|
pg| ***** 15 ***** |


cs|2|at|{ Both the declarer and your partner can see your signals. Knowing your count in a suit  
 will sometimes be more helpful to the declarer. Be careful about when you choose to signal! }
^-
|
pg| ***** 16 ***** |


at|The last of these warnings is particularly important when it comes to count signals. As you know, when a declarer is able to figure out the distribution of the defenders' hands, he is sometimes able to play the hand as if he could see all the cards. Guessing is a normal part of declarer play on a lot of deals. Defenders who give too many count signals will take away a lot of the guesses that the declarer normally would have to make.

At this early point in your study of count signals it is best not to worry about this too much. You will learn through experience some of the situations where your count signals do more harm than good, but here are 2 sensible guidelines to keep in mind:

|
pg| ***** 17 ***** |


cs|3|at|^-{ Do not signal count if you know that this information will not be relevant to your partner. }

|
pg| ***** 18 ***** |


cs|1|at|{ Do not signal count if your partner already knows your count (perhaps from the bidding). }

|
pg| ***** 19 ***** |


ha|y|rh||st||md|1c4,c3,ckqjt9c,ca82|


nt|^b@2^z@3Here is an example to illustrate the power of count signals. You are sitting East. South opened the bidding with 2NT and was raised to 3NT by North. |
pg| ***** 20 ***** |


at|North put down a very nice club suit in the dummy and 8 small cards in the other 3 suits. |
pg| ***** 21 ***** |


at|Your partner's opening lead was won by the declarer who then led the @C4 out of his hand. |
pg| ***** 22 ***** |


pc|c4|at|Your partner followed suit with the @C3 |
pg| ***** 23 ***** |


pc|c|at|and South called for one of dummy's 5 equal clubs. |
pg| ***** 24 ***** |


pc|c|at|Would you take your @CA or not? |
pg| ***** 25 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3Your best strategy as a defender in this situation is to take your @CA at a point when South is out of clubs. We have already seen some examples of when a defender should use the hold up play, but this is arguably the most common (and useful) situation for using that technique on defense. By holding up your @CA until just the right moment, you will be able to minimize the number of tricks that the declarer will be able to win in this suit.|
pg| ***** 26 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3You should definitely hold up at least once because South would not open the bidding with 2NT if he had a singleton club. You might as well start getting into the habit of giving your partner count signals so play the @C2 (as opposed to the @C8) to let your partner know that you have an odd number of clubs. |
pg| ***** 27 ***** |


pc|c2|
pg| ***** 28 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3The declarer leads another club from the dummy. |
pg| ***** 29 ***** |


pc|ck|at|This time you do have a problem as to whether or not you should take your @CA. There are 3 missing small clubs. |
pg| ***** 30 ***** |


md|0c5|at|You know South has at least one of these clubs (because his 2NT opening bid promised a balanced hand), but the location of the other 2 clubs is a mystery. |
pg| ***** 31 ***** |


at|Either winning this trick or ducking your @CA again could be the most effective defense depending on the location of the 2 missing clubs. |
pg| ***** 32 ***** |


md|0c67|

nt|^b@2^z@3If South has all of the outstanding clubs, |
pg| ***** 33 ***** |


at|the play you make now is unlikely to matter. South was dealt more clubs than you were so you cannot hold up your @CA enough times to exhaust his supply of cards in the suit. |
pg| ***** 34 ***** |


md|0,c76|at|If your partner has 2 of the 3 missing clubs |
pg| ***** 35 ***** |


at|then South has exactly one club left |
pg| ***** 36 ***** |


at|and it would be best for the defense if you took your @CA now. |
pg| ***** 37 ***** |


pc|cacc|
pg| ***** 38 ***** |


at|Since declarer has no clubs left in his hand and no other entries to the dummy, North's club winners are stranded. |
pg| ***** 39 ***** |


up|3|md|0c6|

nt|^b@2^z@3If it turns out that your partner has only 1 of the 3 missing clubs, |
pg| ***** 40 ***** |


at|leaving more clubs in the declarer's hand, |
pg| ***** 41 ***** |


at|you will do best to duck your @CA a second time. |
pg| ***** 42 ***** |


pc|c8cc|
pg| ***** 43 ***** |


at|There may not be any point in the declarer playing a third round of clubs now, but if he does you can win your @CA and know that he will never be able to get back to the dummy to enjoy the 2 established club winners. |
pg| ***** 44 ***** |


up|3|md|0c7|

nt|^b@2^z@3To summarize, if South has all 3 of the missing clubs, |
pg| ***** 45 ***** |


at|the play you make on the second round of clubs is unlikely to matter. |
pg| ***** 46 ***** |


md|0,c7|at|If South has 2 of the 3 missing clubs, |
pg| ***** 47 ***** |


at|you will do best to hold up your @CA a second time. |
pg| ***** 48 ***** |


md|0,c6|at|If South has only 1 of the 3 missing clubs, |
pg| ***** 49 ***** |


at|the most effective defense will be to win your @CA on the second round of the suit. |
pg| ***** 50 ***** |


at|Knowing the number of cards that South was dealt in clubs would be a very helpful piece of information for you to have right now! |
pg| ***** 51 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3As you have probably realized, the way in which East can know his best strategy in the club suit |
pg| ***** 52 ***** |


up|4|at|is for West to give him a count signal on the first round of clubs. This is clearly a situation for count signals (as opposed to attitude signals) because clubs is a suit that the declarer has led. Attitude signals do not apply when the defenders are following suit to a trick where the lead came from the declarer or the dummy. |
pg| ***** 53 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3When West has 3 clubs (an odd number), |
pg| ***** 54 ***** |


at|he can pass on that message to his partner by following suit with his lowest club. |
pg| ***** 55 ***** |


pc|c3|at|In this particular example, it will be easy for East to read this signal. He can see the @C2 in his own hand so West's @C3 must be the lowest club that West was dealt. |
pg| ***** 56 ***** |


md|0c76|at|Either West started with a singleton @C3 (leaving South with so many clubs that East's play will not matter) |
pg| ***** 57 ***** |


md|0,c76|at|or West was dealt 3 clubs. |
pg| ***** 58 ***** |


at|East will know to hold up his @CA exactly once. |
pg| ***** 59 ***** |


up|1|md|0c6|

nt|^b@2^z@3If instead West started with 2 clubs (an even number of cards) |
pg| ***** 60 ***** |


at|his count signal should be the higher of his 2 spot cards, the @C7 in this case. |
pg| ***** 61 ***** |


pc|c7|at|Given the dummy's club holding and the fact that East holds the @C8, East knows that the @C7 is West's highest club. |
pg| ***** 62 ***** |


md|0c3|at|The @C7 could be a singleton (in which case East's play does not matter) |
pg| ***** 63 ***** |


md|0,c3|at|or West began with a doubleton club. |
pg| ***** 64 ***** |


at|In that case South still has 2 clubs left and East should hold up his @CA twice. |
pg| ***** 65 ***** |


up|1|

nt|^b@2^z@3In this example hand, West was fortunate to have been dealt spot cards in clubs that were sufficiently high and low to make his count signals clear. As with attitude signals, a defender will not always be dealt spot cards that allow him to clearly convey the message that he would like to send his partner. |
pg| ***** 66 ***** |


md|0c87,c32,,c65|

nt|^b@2^z@3For example, West now has the @C32 doubleton. He would like to tell his partner that he has an even number of clubs, |
pg| ***** 67 ***** |


at|but the best he can do is play the @C3 which is not exactly a high club. |
pg| ***** 68 ***** |


md|0c5,c876,,c32|at|Here West clubs are the @C8, @C7, and @C6. He would like East to know that he has an odd number of clubs, |
pg| ***** 69 ***** |


at|but his lowest club is the @C6 which is a relatively high card as far as spot cards go. All West can do is play this card and hope that East can work out the position.|
pg| ***** 70 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|ht|d|cs|2|at|^-{Defenders are not always dealt the perfect spot cards for the signals that they want 
 to make. All they can do is signal as loudy as possible with the cards that they were dealt. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 71 ***** |


ht|p|at|In all types of signals there will be situations where even the loudest card a player holds will carry an ambiguous message. Even the best defenders sometimes misread each others' signals.|
pg| ***** 72 ***** |


md|1h3,h94,haq5|

nt|^b@2^z@3Here is another card combination that illustrates both the advantages and the possible dangers of using count signals on defense. South, the declarer in a notrump contract, leads the @H3 out of his hand. |
pg| ***** 73 ***** |


pc|h3|at|You are sitting West and since you have 2 hearts (an even number), |
pg| ***** 74 ***** |


at|you can play the @H9 as a count signal. |
pg| ***** 75 ***** |


pc|h9|

md|0hk87,,,hjt62|

nt|^b@2^z@3Why would East care about how many hearts you were dealt in this situation? Well, perhaps the remaining unseen hearts are distributed as above. |
pg| ***** 76 ***** |


at|South wins the first heart trick in the dummy |
pg| ***** 77 ***** |


pc|hq|at|and, for the sake of practice, let's have East give count in hearts as well. East has an even number of hearts (4). He should therefore play the highest heart that he can afford. This happens to be the @H6. |
pg| ***** 78 ***** |


pc|h6|
pg| ***** 79 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3The declarer still has 2 certain heart tricks with high honors in that suit. |
pg| ***** 80 ***** |


at|The good news for the defense is that East's remaining @HJ102 is strong enough to prevent South from winning any further tricks in hearts. The only catch is that East must retain all of his hearts. If he discards from this suit then South will be able to win an undeserved 4th trick in hearts.|
pg| ***** 81 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3Looking at the entire heart suit and none of the other suits, it may be difficult for you to imagine why East would ever discard a heart. Well, East may be faced with a situation where he has to discard ^*Isomething^*N and his holdings in the other 3 suits might look ever more valuable than his holding in hearts. |
pg| ***** 82 ***** |


up|3|

nt|^b@2^z@3When East receives a count signal suggesting that his partner was dealt an even number of hearts, |
pg| ***** 83 ***** |


pc|h9|at|East might wake up and realize that it is critical for him to keep all of his cards in that suit. East can see 4 hearts in his own hand |
pg| ***** 84 ***** |


at|and 3 hearts in the dummy. |
pg| ***** 85 ***** |


at|If the even number of hearts that West started with was 2, |
pg| ***** 86 ***** |


at|then South was dealt 4 hearts. |
pg| ***** 87 ***** |


at|East will be in a position to know that discarding a heart could be very damaging to the defense. |
pg| ***** 88 ***** |


up|2|

nt|^b@2^z@3Now let's take South's @H7 and give it to West. |
pg| ***** 89 ***** |


md|0,h7|

nt|^b@2^z@3The declarer still has exactly 3 winners in hearts between his own hand and the dummy, but since neither South nor North have more than 3 cards in hearts, there is no way that the declarer could ever win more than 3 heart tricks. |
pg| ***** 90 ***** |


at|As such, it is perfectly safe for East to discard a heart. |
pg| ***** 91 ***** |


at|When South leads the @H3 out of his hand, |
pg| ***** 92 ***** |


pc|h3|at|West, who now has an odd number of hearts, will play his lowest heart, the @H4, as a count signal. |
pg| ***** 93 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|pc|h4|at|The dummy wins the trick and East plays the @H6 as a count signal as before. |
pg| ***** 94 ***** |


pc|hqh6|
pg| ***** 95 ***** |


at|East knows that he started with 4 hearts |
pg| ***** 96 ***** |


at|and that the dummy started with 3 hearts. |
pg| ***** 97 ***** |


md|0h97|at|Unless West's @H3 was a singleton (meaning that South has all the rest of the hearts), |
pg| ***** 98 ***** |


md|0,h97|at|East knows from his partner's count signal that West was dealt an odd number of hearts. |
pg| ***** 99 ***** |


at|It will be very likely from East's point of view that South began with exactly 3 cards in hearts. |
pg| ***** 100 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3East can use the information about South's likely heart length |
pg| ***** 101 ***** |


at|to know that, later in the play, he can safely discard a heart without having to worry about giving up a trick in that suit. |
pg| ***** 102 ***** |


md|0h97|at|What if it turns out that West's @H4 was really a singleton and that South started with 5 cards in hearts? |
pg| ***** 103 ***** |


At|In this case a heart discard from East would be a disaster for the defense. Fortunately, East will usually know from the bidding if it is possible that South had been dealt 5 cards in hearts. |
pg| ***** 104 ***** |


md|0,h9|up|4|

nt|^b@2^z@3So far the only consequence that we have seen of West giving a count signal in hearts |
pg| ***** 105 ***** |


at|is that East is able to learn if he needs to hold on to all 4 of his hearts or if it safe to discard from that suit. That can only be a good thing for the defense. |
pg| ***** 106 ***** |


at|However, if we take East's @H10 and exchange it for one of South's spot cards in hearts (let's use the @H7), one of the dangers of using count signals will become apparent. |
pg| ***** 107 ***** |


md|0ht,,,h7|

nt|^b@2^z@3South leads the @H3 as before |
pg| ***** 108 ***** |


pc|h3|at|and West plays the @H9 as a count signal to tell his partner that he has an even number of hearts. |
pg| ***** 109 ***** |


pc|h9|at|This trick is won in the dummy |
pg| ***** 110 ***** |


pc|Hq|at|and East plays the @H7 as a count signal, suggesting that he also has an even number of hearts. |
pg| ***** 111 ***** |


pc|h7|
pg| ***** 112 ***** |


at|Dummy's remaining heart honor is cashed. |
pg| ***** 113 ***** |


pc|ha|at|This declarer happens to be quite astute and he notices that both defenders follow suit with lower cards than they played on the first round of hearts. |
pg| ***** 114 ***** |


pc|hhh|
pg| ***** 115 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3When the third round of hearts is led from the dummy |
pg| ***** 116 ***** |


pc|h|at|and East follows suit with the @H6, |
pg| ***** 117 ***** |


pc|h6|at|South is faced with a choice between playing the @HK and finessing the @H10. |
pg| ***** 118 ***** |


At|The declarer has a guess to make. If East still has the @HJ, the winning play will be to finesse the @H10, |
pg| ***** 119 ***** |


pc|ht|md|0,hj|at|but the finesse will fail if West has the @HJ. |
