nt|^b@2^z@3

nt|^b@2^z@3This is a close decision for the declarer. In the absence of any special information, |
pg| ***** 122 ***** |


at|the correct percentage play is to go up with the @HK on the third round in the hope that the @HJ will fall. |
pg| ***** 123 ***** |


up|10|at|The way that the declarer should play this card combination is not central to the lesson being covered, but it is a useful thing for you to know. |
pg| ***** 124 ***** |


md|0,,,hj|at|A declarer who knows the correct play in hearts would normally win only 3 tricks when East started with 4 hearts headed by the @HJ. |
pg| ***** 125 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3An astute declarer might alter his normal plan in hearts, however, if the defenders decide to use count signals in this suit. |
pg| ***** 126 ***** |


at|In particular, if both defenders play high spot cards on the first round of hearts, the declarer will think that they both started with an even number of hearts. |
pg| ***** 127 ***** |


at|When the time comes for the declarer to make his decision, there is a good chance that he will make the winning play of finessing the @H10 (a play that he would not normally make). |
pg| ***** 128 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3Suppose that only one defender gives an honest count signal. For the sake of argument, assume that West plays the @H9 (the correct count card), but that East plays the @H2 (an incorrect count card since East has an even number of hearts). South will know that one of the defenders is giving false count (because there are 6 hearts missing and there is no way that an even number plus an odd number can add up to 6). |
pg| ***** 129 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3The declarer will have no way of knowing which of the defenders is telling the truth and which of the defenders is giving false count. He may still make the winning guess on the third round of hearts, |
pg| ***** 130 ***** |


at|but his chances of doing so are less than if both defenders had given honest count signals. |
pg| ***** 131 ***** |


at|If both defenders have the presence of mind to give false count in this suit, it is most unlikely that the declarer will figure out what is going on. |
pg| ***** 132 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3This is one card combination in which honest count signals by the defenders rate to help the declarer more than the defense. |
pg| ***** 133 ***** |


at|In fact, the best strategy for the defenders in this card combination is to lie to each other (and to the declarer) about the number of cards that they were dealt in this suit by using false count signals! |
pg| ***** 134 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|ht|d|cs|4|at|^-{ False count means deliberately using the wrong count signal on defense in an effort to 
 mislead declarer. The danger of giving false count is that your partner will also be misled! }
^-
|
pg| ***** 135 ***** |


ht|p|at|When to give false count |
pg| ***** 136 ***** |


at|and when to give true count is a matter of judgment. At this point in your career as a defender you will do best if you usually tell the truth with your signals!|
pg| ***** 137 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3You should know that most introductory books on defense do not even mention the possibility of intentionally giving misleading signals in order to fool the declarer. That may be just as well since it takes a lot of experience to know when to apply this tactic. There is a definite danger in giving false count, especially if you do it a lot - your partner will not know when he should trust your signals and he will sometimes make bad decisions on defense as a result.|
pg| ***** 138 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3It is probably best if you always try to give honest signals on defense given your current level of experience, but you should know that, on occasion, you may win an extra trick or 2 by signaling inaccurately. One of the reasons that it is important for you to know this is so that you will not always trust the count signals that your opponents give when you are the declarer! This is especially true if you are playing against experienced players.|
pg| ***** 139 ***** |


